{"id": 15273, "date": "2020-01-14T05:00:00", "date_gmt": "2020-01-14T13:00:00", "guid": {"rendered": "http://estreetshuffle.com/?p=15273"}, "modified": "2020-01-14T05:15:35", "modified_gmt": "2020-01-14T13:15:35", "slug": "cover-me-ruby-baby", "status": "publish", "type": "post", "link": "https://estreetshuffle.com/index.php/2020/01/14/cover-me-ruby-baby/", "title": {"rendered": "Cover Me: Ruby Baby"}, "content": {"rendered": "<p>You could argue who did it better, The Drifters or Dion and The Belmonts, but either way you&#8217;d be right.</p>\n<p>Written by the great songwriting team of Lieber and Stoller, &#8220;Ruby Baby&#8221; rocks, swings, saunters, and steamrolls in both versions.</p>\n<p>The Drifters came first, releasing their original track in 1956 and notching a #10 berth on the Billboard R&amp;B chart.</p>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><iframe loading=\"lazy\" title=\"Ruby Baby by The Drifters\" width=\"758\" height=\"569\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/CpANME0IS0o?feature=oembed\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share\" referrerpolicy=\"strict-origin-when-cross-origin\" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n<p>Dion&#8217;s 1963 version did even better, peaking at #5 on the R&amp;B chart and all the way at #2 on the Top 100.</p>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><iframe loading=\"lazy\" title=\"Dion And The Belmonts - Ruby Baby\" width=\"758\" height=\"569\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/3u1doOc3njI?feature=oembed\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share\" referrerpolicy=\"strict-origin-when-cross-origin\" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n<p>As for which version of &#8220;Ruby Baby&#8221; influenced Bruce Springsteen and the E Street Band on the only two occasions they performed it, you could once again fairly argue for both.</p>\n<p>Bruce and the band debuted &#8220;Ruby Baby&#8221; at one of their legendary surprise gigs at The Stone Pony on a Sunday night in August 1987. Listen to their performance below, and you&#8217;ll clearly hear the &#8220;hey hey!&#8221; from Dion&#8217;s arrangement as well as Clarence&#8217;s smoking sax solo tribute to the Drifters&#8217; original.</p>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><iframe loading=\"lazy\" title=\"6. Ruby, Ruby (Bruce Springsteen - Live At The Stone Pony 8-2-1987)\" width=\"758\" height=\"569\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/MxyqrGOcEto?feature=oembed\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share\" referrerpolicy=\"strict-origin-when-cross-origin\" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n<p>Exactly one week later, they took another run at it&#8211;but this time in a slower, steamier arrangement that draws on both influences and grounds them on E Street.</p>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><iframe loading=\"lazy\" title=\"Bruce Springsteen - RUBY RUBY 1987 (audio)\" width=\"758\" height=\"569\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/wyJtkd3w6HQ?feature=oembed\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share\" referrerpolicy=\"strict-origin-when-cross-origin\" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n<p>Although neither recording is as clear as we&#8217;d like, it&#8217;s still easy to hear just how much fun the band has with the classic R&amp;B track&#8211;why this one hasn&#8217;t shown up in Bruce&#8217;s set lists since is hard to fathom.</p>\n<p><strong>Ruby Baby<br />\nFirst performed:</strong> August 2, 1987 (Asbury Park, NJ)<br />\n<strong>Last performed:</strong> August 9, 1987 (Asbury Park, NJ)</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n", "protected": false}, "excerpt": {"rendered": "<p>Twice only: Bruce Springsteen and the E Street Band turn in steamy performances of &#8220;Ruby Baby&#8221; at The Stone Pony in the summer of 1987.</p